Section 6The Typesetting Advantage

In a previous section of this manual, we provided you with some typesetting terminology. This section discusses how we can imbed these typesetting commands into the text for better control of the typeset output.


The Syntax of Imbedded Control Words
Typesetting commands, such as changing fonts, margins, and others maybe imbedded in the text. All such commands are enclosed in square brackets []. Multiple commands may be entered in the same brackets if you separate them by either commas or semicolons. These commands are described below.


The Typesetting Advantage
The word "Typesetting" refers to the creation of text (or an image) and then transferring that image to an electronic device (such as a printer or a screen.) In this section we will discuss the creation process only. Future sections will show you how to transfer this image to an electronic output device, namely the printer.
Now that you are familiar with some typesetting terminology, let us create a page using these terms. 
Imagine (or take out) a blank sheet of paper and draw a box in it. Suppose we decide to write some text on this sheet of paper.  Where would you place it? How far down the page should the text begin? or how far to the right? These measures are termed  MARGINS. There are four margins: top, bottom, left, right.

     PICTURE

They maybe set in several different units of measure (inches, centimeters, picas, etc.) Now think about the text. How much text should you fit  on one page ? How long should each line be ? Obviously by setting these margins you are restricted to a certain PAGE LENGTH (amount of lines on a page) and a certain LINE LENGTH (amount of characters on a line.)

Many of these restrictions depend upon the CHARACTER SIZE (how small or large each character is) and the space between two lines (or LEADING.) 
   You will fit fewer lines using large letters and the opposite applies if you use small letters.
