Finding fonts                          
Now that we have the text, what about the typeface ? Many fonts (and sizes of character fonts) are available on the Amiga. This is of course dependent upon the kind of printer you own. If you have a dot matrix printer you may choose any of the standard Amiga fonts (a complete listing can be found in the Appendix.)
If you have an HP LaserJet or compatible printer you can choose any of the laser fonts available on the LaserJet.
You may expand this list of fonts by buying separate font sets (if available) from your Amiga dealer.


Defining fonts                         
You must tell C‚i‚t‚y‚ ‚D‚e‚s‚k‚ if you want a text font other than the default (which is Topaz 8). You may alter this default in three ways: by pulling the "EDIT TEXT ATTRIBUTES" submenu from Preferences, by pressing the right mouse button on the "ABC" tool (both discussed in the Tutorial), or by imbedding a typesetting command in the text that defines the new font. 
The command to define fonts in C‚i‚t‚y‚ ‚D‚e‚s‚k‚ follows below:

  [font n„a„m„e„ „n„] sets the font name and the font size to n„. n„ is optional
  [fsize n„] sets the font size to n„.
  [n„a„m„e„ „n„] changes font to n„a„m„e„ and size to n„.
Examples:

  [font d„i„a„m„o„n„d„ „1„2„] is the same as [font d„i„a„m„o„n„d„,fsize 1„2„]
  [e„m„e„r„a„l„d„ „2„0„] is a shorthand for [font e„m„e„r„a„l„d„,fsize 2„0„]
  [g„a„r„n„e„t„] is equivalent to [font g„a„r„n„e„t„]


Alternating fonts                         
"I like the fonts.., but how do I interchange among them ..?" Alternating fonts in a line of text or even changing fonts in characters on a single line of text is accomplished in C‚i‚t‚y‚ ‚D‚e‚s‚k‚ by imbedding a typesetting command within the text. Example:

  [d„i„a„m„o„n„d„] This is diamond [o„p„a„l„ „1„1„] this is opal 11.
  [s„a„p„p„h„i„r„e„ „1„5„]E[r„u„b„y„ „8„]a[t„o„p„a„z„ „8„]a[g„a„r„n„e„t„ „9„]c[m„i„c„r„o„ „6„]h [t„o„p„a„z„ „8„]character is different.


The above commands will produce:

  THIS IS DIAMOND this is opal 11.
